# Oyabaun project

- **Stack**: Rust/WASM client (`client/`), specialized Go WebSocket relay (`relay/`), shared message contracts (`protocol/`). Docker Compose in `infra/`.
- **Tone**: Dark neo-Tokyo / yakuza FPS; retro presentation, modern netcode split (authoritative server for hits/health/spawn; client prediction for local movement feel).
- **Nostr**: Pubkey is long-term identity. Only **auth** uses signed Nostr events (or NIP-07 in browser). After verify, relay issues a **short-lived session token**. Gameplay messages carry token + room id, not per-frame signatures.
- **Relay is the gameplay bus**: All realtime **client ↔ gameplay** communication goes through the **Oyabaun WebSocket relay** (join, snaps, input, events). Do **not** add alternate gameplay transports (P2P WebRTC, direct client sockets, or “side channels”) for match state unless explicitly scoped as a separate experiment. Nostr remains identity/auth and optional out-of-band signaling—not the authoritative tick stream.
- **Do not** bolt on a generic Nostr relay; keep the Go server minimal and game-specific.
- **Persistence**: Prefer in-memory relay state for MVP; add Postgres only if a feature truly needs it.
- **Changes**: Minimal diffs, match existing style, no drive-by refactors or unsolicited markdown files.
- **Git**: After finishing a coherent set of code or config changes, commit on the current branch with a short, imperative message (present tense, one line when possible) so history stays traceable. Prefer small logical commits over one huge dump.
- **Level art & world detail**: Build in **Blender** and ship via exported `client/levels/*.glb`. Do **not** add client-side procedural world geometry, runtime “dressing” meshes merged into `GltfLevelCpu`, or similar hacks for storefronts/signage/detail unless the user **explicitly** requests that approach.
- **World characters (humanoids)**: Use the skinned glTF `client/characters/yakuza_shooter.glb` for boss, rival, and remotes — **not** pixel-atlas NPC billboards. Murals/VFX may still use the billboard pass in `render.rs`.
- **Dev commands — agent runs them**: The user’s usual workflow is **only** starting/stopping the stack (`oyabaunctl launch` / `stop`). When a task needs `export-world`, `rebuild-level`, `redesign-tokyo-phase1`, `enhance-tokyo-alley`, `wasm-pack`, or headless Blender, the **agent must execute** those commands in the environment and report results — **do not** hand the user a block of shell commands to run themselves unless they explicitly ask for instructions.
- **Uncertainty**: If requirements are ambiguous or conflict with the art pipeline (e.g. “more street detail” without a Blender change), **ask** before inventing workarounds. Prefer a short clarification over shipping a clever approximation the user did not want.

When changing wire format, update `docs/PROTOCOL.md` and keep client/relay parsers in sync.
